  "prompt": "How much of demonetized money, might not come back to the banking system?",
  "response": "It's difficult to provide an exact figure on how much demonetized money might not come back to the banking system, as this can vary depending on specific circumstances in different countries and the effectiveness of the demonetization policy. However, I can provide some general insights and examples.\n\nWhen a government decides to demonetize certain currency notes, the primary goals are often to combat corruption, black money, and counterfeit currency. The expectation is that people holding undeclared or illicit cash will have difficulty depositing it into banks without facing scrutiny from tax authorities.\n\nIn the case of India's 2016 demonetization, the government invalidated 86% of the currency in circulation overnight. According to the Reserve Bank of India's annual report for 2016-17, about 99% of the demonetized currency eventually returned to the banking system. This high return rate suggested that the policy may not have been as effective in curbing black money as initially hoped.\n\nThe amount of demonetized money that doesn't return to the banking system can be influenced by various factors:\n\n1. **Public awareness and compliance**: If people are aware of the demonetization and believe in the government's ability to track illicit deposits, they may be less likely to attempt to deposit undeclared cash.\n\n2. **Alternative investment options**: Those holding black money might invest in gold, real estate, or other assets instead of trying to deposit the cash into banks.\n\n3. **Stringency of bank monitoring**: The more rigorous the monitoring and reporting requirements for banks, the less likely people will be to deposit undeclared cash.\n\n4. **Timeframe for exchange**: A shorter window for exchanging old notes can make it more difficult for people to launder their money through the banking system.\n\n5. **Public trust in the banking system**: If people have confidence in the banking system and believe their money will be safe, they may be more likely to deposit their cash.\n\nGiven these factors, the amount of demonetized money that doesn't return to the banking system can range from a small percentage to potentially larger amounts, depending on the specific circumstances and effectiveness of the policy implementation. In some cases, it might be as low as 1-2%, while in others, it could be higher, but exact figures are challenging to predict without specific data from a particular demonetization event.",
